---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
---

<DocsLayout
	title="style skill"
	description="The style skill writes CSS following Tideway's tokens and strict BEM conventions."
	active="style"
>
	<article class="doc">
		<p class="doc__eyebrow">Skill</p>
		<h1 class="doc__title">style</h1>
		<p class="doc__lead">
			Writes CSS the Tideway way: every value from a token, every class in strict BEM, as plain CSS
			with no build step. Use it whenever you're styling a component or page in a Tideway project.
		</p>

		<section class="doc__section">
			<h2 class="doc__section-title">The rules it follows</h2>
			<div class="doc__list">
				<p class="doc__item">
					<strong>Every value comes from a token.</strong> Colors, spacing, type, radii, shadows, and
					breakpoints all come from the <a class="doc__link" href="/docs/colors">token scales</a> —
					never an off-scale value.
				</p>
				<p class="doc__item">
					<strong>Reference tokens as custom properties.</strong> Write
					<code class="doc__code">padding: var(--space-4)</code>, not the raw value, so the link to the
					token survives.
				</p>
				<p class="doc__item">
					<strong>Every class is strict BEM</strong> — <code class="doc__code">block__element--modifier</code>,
					one block per component, elements flat even when the DOM nests.
				</p>
				<p class="doc__item">
					<strong>Selectors stay flat.</strong> One class per selector, no IDs, no bare element
					selectors outside the reset, and no <code class="doc__code">!important</code>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="doc__section">
			<h2 class="doc__section-title">Workflow</h2>
			<div class="doc__list">
				<p class="doc__item">Create a <code class="doc__code">tokens.css</code> declaring the custom properties the project uses, imported first.</p>
				<p class="doc__item">Style one block per component, keeping all of a block's CSS together.</p>
				<p class="doc__item">Media queries use the breakpoint tokens, mobile-first (<code class="doc__code">min-width</code>).</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="doc__section">
			<h2 class="doc__section-title">File organization</h2>
			<p class="doc__lead">
				Tideway doesn't impose a file layout — it follows whatever convention the project already has.
			</p>
			<div class="doc__list">
				<p class="doc__item">
					<strong>One component per file</strong> (<code class="doc__code">Tabs.jsx</code>): give it a
					matching stylesheet (<code class="doc__code">Tabs.css</code>).
				</p>
				<p class="doc__item">
					<strong>Grouped components:</strong> if the project already bundles related components into
					one file, it's fine to bundle their styles the same way.
				</p>
				<p class="doc__item">
					<strong>Plain CSS with no components to mirror:</strong> organize by purpose
					(<code class="doc__code">theme.css</code>, <code class="doc__code">layout.css</code>,
					<code class="doc__code">forms.css</code>) or, for a multi-page project, by page.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>
	</article>
</DocsLayout>
